<subSubSection id="0DE057B8EAD2C768B1781902ED861CC0" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="46F98843DA5041F9EA34CE268D2E8328" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19F6E935DEC50B7D8ABE5E3437676407" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">
Named for Carol C. Horvitz in recognition of her many contributions to the understanding of the ecology and evolution of 
<taxonomicName id="429F2F1DEA7ACB1593843805BA20DF29" genus="Zingiberales" lsidName="Zingiberales" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" rank="genus">Zingiberales</taxonomicName>
and their interactions with pollinators, seed dispersers, and insect herbivores and her collegiality over the years. Also in recognition of her mentorship to new generations of resesearchers. The name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2869E287365ABDB8A15ED99D25FDC332" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="294008E8CB358F130797BBDFA074CBE9" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7007225F1DF88091B827D997335C5D28" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="ABCF594A63D18B66EF1D4EDBDEEF0755" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephaloleia antennata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">Cephaloleia antennata</taxonomicName>
. It can be distinguished by the vertex of the head having a medial carina, by the pronotum lacking an oblique impression, and by the smaller size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
